NAME: Abbeyleix House
COMPOSITION: Single-arch rubble stone hump back road bridge over river, c. 1840, with cut granite voussoirs.

NAME: Abbeyleix House
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay three-storey over basement Classical style country house with dormer attic, begun 1773, with pedimented breakfront having cut stone Doric doorcase to ground floor. Five-bay elevation to garden front with breakfront having cut sandstone doorcase and Wyatt style window openings to flanking bays. Two-bay single-storey wing to west, renovated c. 1840, with façade enrichments added. Extended to west, post-1902, comprising seven-bay single-storey wing with breakfront having three-bay advanced centre bay.  Balustraded forecourt, c. 1840, to north.  Formal gardens, post-1839, to south comprising series of artificial terraces with balustrades, flights of steps and ha-has.

NAME: Abbeyleix House
COMPOSITION: Multiple-bay two-storey stable complex, c. 1800, on a quadrangular plan with courtyard. Pair of round-headed integral carriageways with belfry and ogee dome to east and series of elliptical-headed carriageways. Multiple-bay two-storey range, c. 1800, to east on a triangular plan with courtyard (kitchen) connecting to Abbeyleix House.  Detached four-bay single-storey rubble stone stable range, c. 1800, to west.

NAME: Tower Cross Roads Lodge

NAME: Heywood Gardens
COMPOSITION: Freestanding sham castle folly, c. 1780, with corner turrets on circular plans.

NAME: Heywood Gardens
COMPOSITION: Freestanding five-bay Georgian Gothic summerhouse or orangery, c. 1780.

COMPOSITION: Detached single-storey late-Georgian villa with dormer attic, c. 1825, with single- and two-storey bows. Stable complex to site. Detached gate lodge to site.

NAME: Mounthrath Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached two-bay Church of Ireland church, c. 1820, with gabled projecting bay. Extended to rear comprising single-storey return. Two-storey former school attached to rear. Former schoolhouse may have last been used as a Sexton's House.

NAME: Kilmartin House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey Regency style house, c. 1820, with projecting ground floor having balcony over. Renovated, c. 1990.

NAME: Quakers Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch road bridge over river Nore, c. 1800.

NAME: Moneymore Bridge
COMPOSITION: Three-arch road bridge over river, c. 1800, with triangular cut-waters.

NAME: Skirk Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, c. 1750, with tower and vestry projection. Now in ruins. Ruins of earlier church to south.

NAME: Borris-in-Ossory Courthouse
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey former courthouse, c. 1828. Renovated, c. 1990. Interior retains original fittings to courtroom. Now in use as County Council offices.

NAME: Borris-in-Ossory Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Hiberno Romanesque Church of Ireland church, c. 1870, with round tower style bell tower and vestry projection.

NAME: Townparks School
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey former school, c. 1870, with gabled projecting porch, stair return and pair of wings to rear on C-shaped plans about a courtyard. Extended comprising single- and two-storey ranges with conservatory added. Now in residential use.
Detached three-bay three-storey house, c. 1890, with projecting porch and two-storey return to rear.

NAME: Borris-in-Ossory Market House
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace three-bay two-storey former market house, dated 1882. Now in use as store.

NAME: Ballybrophy Railway Station
COMPOSITION: Detached Tudor Revival railway station, c. 1855, with projecting porch and gables. Detached railway goods shed, c. 1900, to site.

NAME: Glebe Farm
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1820.

NAME: Aghaboe Grange House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey Victorian house, c. 1880, with veranda to front having gablet over entrance.

NAME: Aghaboe Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, built 1818, with tower having castellated upper stage on an octagonal plan and vestry projection. Fragments of medieval stone work salvaged from nearby abbey.

NAME: Aghaboe House
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey Georgian house, c. 1730, with pedimented doorcase. May incorporate 17th century fabric.

NAME: Poorman's Bridge
COMPOSITION: Seven-arch limestone road bridge over river Nore, c. 1770, with triangular cut-waters.

NAME: Norefields House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey over basement Georgian house, c. 1810, with single-bay two-storey flanking wings. Renovated and extended to rear, c. 1985, comprising single-storey over basement return to accommodate use as guesthouse.

NAME: Old Laundry
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey cottage, c. 1820, with gabled projecting bay to centre. Renovated and extended to rear, c. 1885, comprising three-bay single-storey return with dormer attic with gabled projecting porch added to front. Now in commercial use.
Detached nine-bay five-storey former corn mill, c. 1870.

NAME: Millbrook House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey Victorian house with dormer attic, dated 1885, built as agent's house with full-height advanced bay to left having box bay window to ground floor.

NAME: Blackhill House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1810, incorporating fabric of earlier house to rear with wings. Renovated, c. 1920, with projecting glazed porch added. Now in use as nursing home.

NAME: Farmleigh House
COMPOSITION: Gateway, c. 1820. Detached two-storey outbuilding, c. 1820, to site. Group of detached outbuildings, c. 1980, to site. Remainder of estate (including house) demolished with site cleared. Artist Francis Bacon lived here for a short while with his grandmother, Winifred Margaret Supple.

NAME: Fruit Lawn House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey Georgian house, c. 1800. Stable complex to site. Now derelict.

NAME: New Bridge
COMPOSITION: Four-arch road bridge over river Nore, dated 1760, with triangular cut-waters and rubble stone parapets having inscribed plaque. Inscription reads : "1760/this bridge was/erected at the county/expense/Edward Brereton of/Spring Mount Esq/Director/Michael Dealy Mason".

NAME: Gortnaclea House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, c. 1840, with projecting glazed porch to front and two-storey return to rear.

NAME: Shanahoe House
COMPOSITION: Detached two-storey over basement early-Victorian Italianate house, c. 1840, with three-bay ashlar loggia and advanced bay to right.

NAME: Springmount House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, c. 1750, with pedimented bay to centre. Renovated, c. 1870, with façade enrichments added. Renovated, c. 1980, with projecting porch added.

NAME: Abbeyleix Demesne Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached Georgian Church of Ireland church, c. 1765, with tower. Renovated, c. 1880, with transepts added. Now in use as private chapel. Alfred Gilbert designer of tomb of Eustace Besey.
Detached three-bay two-storey late-Victorian house, c. 1875, with canted bay window to left and full-height advanced end bay to right.

NAME: Abbeyleix Demesne Home Farm
COMPOSITION: Stable complex, c. 1840, on a square plan.

NAME: Saint Patrick's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay Gothic Revival Catholic church, dated 1840, retaining original aspect with tower on an octagonal plan and sacristy projection. Interior retains original aspect. Stained glass designed by Mayer & Co, Munich.

NAME: Ballyroan Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay Georgian Church of Ireland church, c. 1800, with chancel, vestry projection and bellcote to gable. Renovated, c. 1860, with projecting porch added to vestry.

NAME: O'Nuallain
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey split-level house, c. 1650, with integral carriageway. Renovated and extended to right, c. 1750, comprising projecting wing on an L-shaped plan. Renovated, c. 1880, with projecting shopfront inserted to part ground floor.
Terraced three-bay two-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1820, with full-height return to rear. Extended to rear comprising two-storey return.
Terraced four-bay two-storey house, c. 1895. Renovated, c. 1935, with ground floor converted to commercial use having rendered pilasters. Pubfront renovated, c. 1990, with canopy inserted.

NAME: Glenbrook House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey Glebe House, c. 1820.

NAME: Saint Lazerian's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay Gothic Revival Catholic church, dated 1847, on a cruciform plan with sacristy projection and bellcote to gable.

NAME: Blandsfort House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey over basement early-Georgian house, c. 1715, possibly originally two-storey. Renovated with projecting porch added (and possibly with top floor added). Stable complex, dated 1792, to site.
Remains of detached two-storey former house, c. 1770, comprising fragments of gable wall.

NAME: Church of the Holy Rosary
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay Catholic church, c. 1840, on a cruciform plan. Extensively renovated, c. 1985.

NAME: Rathaspick Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, dated 1813, with tower having pinnacles. Now in ruins.

NAME: Milltown House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1825, with two-storey return to rear. Single-bay single-storey outbuilding. Stable complex to rear.

NAME: Corbally House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey Georgian house, c. 1770. Remodelled and extended, c. 1915, comprising two-storey return with full-height canted bays added to front and to rear.

NAME: Saint Mary's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay gable-fronted Catholic church, c. 1860, with gabled flanking porches, chancel and pair of sacristy projections. Extensively renovated, c. 1980, with interior remodelled.

NAME: Wolfhill Railway Bridges
COMPOSITION: Pair of reinforced concrete railway bridges over road, c. 1917, with sandstone abutments to one bridge and concrete abutments to other bridge. One of first standard gauge railways laid in Ireland. Opened Sept. 1918, closed 1929.

NAME: Gracefield House
COMPOSITION: Detached cottage orne style house, c. 1817.

NAME: Ballylynan Hall (Saint Anne's Catholic Church)
COMPOSITION: Detached former Catholic church, c. 1830, on a cruciform plan with projecting porch and transepts having bellcote. Renovated and extended, c. 1990, with interior remodelled to accommodate use as hall.

NAME: Ballylynan Courthouse
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey former courthouse, c. 1830, on an L-shaped plan with pair of pavilion style flanking porches and two-storey return to rear. Now in residential use.

NAME: Killabban Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached Church of Ireland church, c. 1800, with Georgian Gothic style tower. Renovated and extended, c. 1865, with chancel and vestry projection added.

NAME: Castletown House
COMPOSITION: Detached two-storey glebe house, c. 1830, on a T-shaped plan.

NAME: Kilmorony House
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached five-bay two-storey over basement Georgian house, c. 1790, with projecting porch. Now in ruins.

NAME: Kilmorony Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-span cast-iron bridge, c. 1840.

NAME: Saint Abban's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached two-bay Gothic Revival Catholic church, c. 1875, with tower, chancel and sacristy projection. Stained glass by Mayer & Co.

NAME: Maganey Bridge
COMPOSITION: Five-arch limestone road bridge over river Barrow, c. 1800, with cut-waters having granite ashlar roundels over and arches over towpaths.

NAME: Killadooley Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay gable-fronted Catholic church, c. 1840, on a rectangular plan with gabled projecting porch and sacristy projection. Interior retains gallery.

NAME: Errill Cross
COMPOSITION: Remains of freestanding limestone ashlar cross, erected 1622, comprising shaft on chamfered base.

NAME: Rathsaran Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, built 1797, with three-stage tower and vestry projection.

NAME: Donaghmore Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, dated 1821, with tower and vestry projection. Plaque above entrance reads : "This church built in the year 1821/during the episcopacy of the Right Rev Robert/Fowler Lord Biship of Ossory/The Revd John Lowry Rector/Revd Richard Kennedy and Mr Luke Kingsmill/church wardens/Mr Patrick Bergin Architect/total expence 520 pounds sterl".

NAME: Mooney's
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, c. 1900, with full-height return to rear. Renovated and extended to rear, c. 1990, comprising single-storey return with replacement pubfront inserted to ground floor.
Detached five-bay two-storey house, c. 1850. Group of detached outbuildings to side and to rear.

Corn mill and malting complex, c. 1930, comprising group of detached buildings (located on either side of river) including three-storey store. Now derelict. Remainder of outbuildings renovated, c. 1990.

NAME: Saint Columba's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay Catholic church, c. 1840, on a T-shaped plan with sacristy projection to rear. Now disused.

NAME: Saint Canice's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached Gothic Revival Catholic church, dated 1871, with tower to corner and side aisles. Interior retains gallery.

NAME: Ballacolla School
COMPOSITION: Detached single-storey school, dated 1889, with gabled projecting porch. Extended to rear, c. 1975.

NAME: Killermogh Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached two-bay Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, c. 1800, with tower, chancel and vestry projection.

NAME: Rathmakelly Glebe
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey rectory, c. 1840. Group of detached single-storey outbuildings to side.

NAME: Bluegate Cottages
COMPOSITION: Group of fourteen semi-detached two-storey estate houses, c. 1890. Individually renovated. Arranged in seven pairs.

NAME: Bluegate House
COMPOSITION: Detached single-storey Tudor Revival former school with dormer attic, c. 1880, on a cruciform plan with gabled canopy over door opening and projecting porch to side. Now in residential use.

NAME: Newtown Bridge
COMPOSITION: Four-arch rubble limestone road bridge over river Goul, c. 1770, with triangular cut-waters having U-shaped recess over to one side. Reinforced, c. 1975, with concrete.

NAME: Newtown Mills
COMPOSITION: Detached ten-bay four-storey corn mill, c. 1880. Detached two-storey over basement mill house, c. 1840, to site.

NAME: Moyne House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, c. 1730, with pedimented bay to centre having projecting porch to ground floor. Renovated and extended, c. 1880, comprising two-bay two-storey wings with dormer attic to left having box bay windows to ground floor.

NAME: Abbeyleix House
COMPOSITION: Underground passage, c. 1840, connecting stable complex to Home Farm with gable-fronted entrance bay to south and series of open rooflights to east.

NAME: Abbeyleix House
COMPOSITION: Freestanding stone icehouse, c. 1800, with pedimented entrance bay to north having segmental-headed door opening; now disused and mostly ovegrown.

NAME: Knapton's Bridge (Monk's Bridge)
COMPOSITION: Eight-arch rubble stone road bridge over river, c. 1775, with rubble stone voussoirs and cut stone triangular cut-waters to north.

NAME: Abbeyleix House
COMPOSITION: Viewing/fishing platform over river, c. 1840, on a half-octagonal plan with sections of wrought-iron railings having concrete piers and urns.

NAME: Abbeyleix House
COMPOSITION: Freestanding six-bay single-storey boathouse, c. 1850, with yellow brick piers and open gable ends.

NAME: Heywood Gardens
COMPOSITION: Arts-and-Crafts style ornamental garden, completed 1912, comprising stone walled garden on a circular plan with summerhouse and fountain. Designed by Sir Edwin Lutyens and planted by Gertrude Jekyll.

NAME: Heywood Gardens
COMPOSITION: Freestanding boathouse, c. 1800, with two vaulted chamfers.

NAME: Heywood Gardens
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Ziggurat type neo-Classical mausoleum, c. 1790.
Freestanding limestone ashlar milestone, c. 1800, on a square plan.

NAME: Fleming's Fireclays
COMPOSITION: Pair of freestanding brick firing kilns, c. 1935, on hemispherical plans. Pair of freestanding chimneys, dated 1948 and 1953, to site.

NAME: Fleming's Fireclays
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay single-storey brick factory manager's house with dormer attic, c. 1940, on an L-shaped plan with half-hipped gabled bay to left. Plaque on west wall commemorates Patrick Joseph Fleming, Patron of Works and Patriot.

NAME: Church of the Sacred Heart
COMPOSITION: Detached Gothic Revival Catholic church, built 1865, with tower, side aisles, polygonal chancel and sacristy projection to rear. Designed by Pugin and Ashlin, architects.

NAME: Grace Mausoleum
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Georgian Gothic mausoleum, dated 1818. Wall-mounted memorial plaques date to pre-1818.

NAME: Providence Lodge
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, c. 1830, with return to rear. Detached two-storey stable building to rear.

NAME: Ashfield Hall
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey Palladian style house with dormer attic, c. 1750, with pedimented advanced entrance bay. Now derelict.

NAME: Ashfield Hall
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey Tudor Gothic style gate lodge with dormer attic, c. 1870, with gabled projecting entrance bay, oriel window and box bay window to right. Extended to rear comprising lean-to return. Now derelict.

NAME: Cooper's Hill House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey early-Georgian house, dated 1717. Extended, c. 1775. Extended, c. 1860, comprising four-bay two-storey wing.

NAME: Church of the Holy Cross
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay Georgian Gothic style Catholic church, c. 1820, with tower, corner turrets on octagonal plans and gabled sacristy projection. Renovated, c. 1985, with interior remodelled.

NAME: Anneville House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, c. 1890, incorporating fabric of earlier house, c. 1800, to rear.

NAME: Hollymount House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over basement Georgian house, c. 1800, with full-height bow to rear. Extended to right comprising two-bay two-storey range. Four-bay two-storey stable block.

NAME: Aghmacart Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached two-bay gable-fronted Church of Ireland church, c. 1820, with gabled projecting porch and bellcote to gable.

NAME: Belmont House
COMPOSITION: Detached single-storey house, c. 1860, with loggia to front, canted bay windows and advanced end bays.

NAME: Saint Brigid's Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, built 1821. Renovated, c. 1860, with tower, projecting porch and vestry projection added. Now disused.

NAME: Glebe Rectory
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey former rectory, c. 1750. Extended, c. 1825, comprising five-bay range. Detached three-bay coach house, c. 1750, to site with pedimented central breakfront. Detached gate lodge, c. 1850, to site.

NAME: Grenan School
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey former school, c. 1880, with gabled projecting entrance bay. Now in residential use.

NAME: Grennan House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey over basement house with part dormer attic, begun c. 1650, with single-bay single-storey wing to right and series of returns to rear. Stable complex to site.

NAME: Tallyho Bridge
COMPOSITION: Five-arch limestone road bridge over river Nore, c. 1800, with triangular cut-waters.

NAME: Knocknatrina House
COMPOSITION: Detached two-storey Tudor Revival former house, c. 1860, with canted bay windows, full-height gabled bowed bays and two-storey wing. Now in ruins. Stable complex to rear.

NAME: Clonageera House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over basement Georgian house, completed 1803, with Doric portico to front and incorporating fabric of earlier house, c. 1725, to rear. Stable complex to site. Walled garden to site on a circular plan.

NAME: Edmondsbury House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey early-Georgian house, c. 1740. Extended, c. 1990, comprising three-bay single-storey wing.

NAME: Killeshin Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay Georgian Gothic style Church of Ireland church, c. 1830, with spire and chancel.

NAME: Everton House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey Georgian house, c. 1800, on an L-shaped plan with entrance bay having full-height flanking bows and bowed ends. Extended comprising three-bay two-storey wing.

NAME: Springhill House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey Georgian house, c. 1740. Group of detached outbuildings to site.

NAME: Tinneel Society of Friends Burial Ground
COMPOSITION: Quaker graveyard with various plots, c. 1725 to the present. Gateway, c. 1800, to site.

NAME: Saint Mary's Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached gable-fronted Church of Ireland church, c. 1795. Renovated, 1830, with chancel added. Extended, c. 1865, with tower and side aisle added. Renovated, c. 1980.
Detached four-bay two-storey house, c. 1840.

NAME: Saint Brigid's Well
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Gothic arch enclosure, c. 1800, over holy well.
Terraced five-bay two-storey house, dated 1733, possibly originally detached. Originally thatched. Extensively renovated, c. 1980, to accommodate commercial use.

NAME: Capard Windmill
COMPOSITION: Remains of freestanding former windmill, c. 1840, comprising stump on a circular plan. Now in ruins.

NAME: Saint Brigid's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Gateway, c. 1860, comprising piers with rubble stone walls having cut limestone stiles and wrought-iron gates. Site of former Church to site. Church now demolished with site cleared.

NAME: Arlington House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey over basement Georgian house, c. 1730, with pedimented central breakfront. Now derelict.

NAME: Le Quartier Francais
COMPOSITION: Terraced five-bay three-storey house, c. 1800, with integral carriageway. Extensively renovated, c. 1880, with timber pubfront inserted to ground floor. Now in commercial use.

NAME: Saint Paul's Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached Gothic Revival Church of Ireland church, built 1851, on a cruciform plan possibly incorporating fabric of earlier Huguenot church, c. 1696.

NAME: Portarlington Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached late-Georgian style church, c. 1830. Deconsecrated, c. 1885. Spire removed, 1924. Now in use as community hall.
Detached five-bay three-storey Georgian house, c. 1780, on a corner site. Renovated, c. 1900, with ground floor partly remodelled to accommodate commercial use.

NAME: The Ramble Inn
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace four-bay three-storey house, c. 1830, originally with integral carriageway to ground floor. Renovated, c. 1980, with ground floor remodelled to accommodate commercial use.

NAME: Finnegan Racing
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace six-bay three-storey house, c. 1830, possibly originally two separate three-bay houses. Renovated, c. 1980, with shopfronts inserted to ground floor.

NAME: Portarlington Market House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey mid-Georgian former market house, c. 1740. Renovated, c. 1990, to accommodate use as garage to ground floor having residential accommodation over.

NAME: The Anvil Inn
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace seven-bay three-storey house, c. 1840, on a corner site with three-bay two-storey return to rear incorporating fabric of earlier building, c. 1770. Renovated, c. 1975, with ground floor remodelled to accommodate commercial use. Renovated, c. 1998.

NAME: Portarlington Catholic Club
COMPOSITION: Terraced five-bay two-storey over basement former house, c. 1820. Renovated, c. 1980, with façade remodelled. Now in use as hall.

Detached five-bay two-storey over basement house, c. 1780. Renovated and extended, c. 1880, with projecting bay added to front, full-height return and projecting porch added to rear. Now in use as offices.

NAME: Allied Irish Bank
COMPOSITION: Three-bay single-storey banking hall, c. 1926.

NAME: Melrose House
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace four-bay two-storey Georgian house, c. 1770.

NAME: Portarlington Garda Station
COMPOSITION: Terraced five-bay three-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1830, with integral carriageway. Now in use as Garda station.

NAME: Matthew's Coffee Shop
COMPOSITION: Terraced five-bay three-storey Georgian building, c. 1800, with full-height returns to rear. Renovated, c. 1985, with ground floor converted to commercial use.

NAME: Cooltedery School
COMPOSITION: Terraced six-bay two-storey former school, c. 1840, with integral carriageway. Now in use as hall.
Terraced three-bay two-storey house, c. 1825. Façade re-rendered, c. 1930.
Terraced two-bay three-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1815.

NAME: Higgins Builders
COMPOSITION: Terraced five-bay three-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1820. Renovated, c. 1870, with façade enrichments added. Renovated, c. 1990, to accommodate commercial use.

NAME: Foxcroft House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey house, c. 1750. Renovated and subdivided (into three separate houses). Individually extended. Group of detached outbuildings to site.
Terraced four-bay two-storey house, c. 1820, incorporating fabric of earlier three-storey single-pile house, c. 1710. Extended comprising two-storey range.

NAME: The Wilton
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey Georgian house, c. 1750, on an L-shaped plan with pedimented Gibbsian style doorcase.

NAME: Bank of Ireland
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over basement Georgian former house, c. 1830. Renovated, c. 1890, with ground floor partly remodelled to accommodate use as bank.
Detached five-bay three-storey over basement Georgian house, c. 1800, with stair return to rear.

NAME: Portarlington Gospel Hall
COMPOSITION: Detached Gothic Revival former Methodist chapel, dated 1904, on a T-shaped plan with projecting porch. Extended, c. 1980, with funerary chapel added to rear. Now in use as gospel hall.

NAME: East End Hotel
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay three-storey mid-Georgian house, c. 1760. Extended, c. 1970, comprising single-storey end bays to sides and three-storey return to rear to accommodate use as hotel. Interior retains Rococo plasterwork to entrance hall.
Semi-detached four-bay two-storey over basement house, c. 1820, with wing. Renovated, c. 1920, with ground floor remodelled. One of a pair.
Semi-detached four-bay two-storey over basement house, c. 1820, with integral carriageway. One of a pair.

NAME: The Elms
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over basement late-Georgian house, built 1789, with single-storey over basement lateral wings incorporating fabric of earlier building. Group of detached outbuildings to site.

NAME: Laurel
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay two-storey over basement house with dormer attic, c. 1820.
Terraced three-bay three-storey house, c. 1870, with integral carriageway. One of a pair.

NAME: Ivy House
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, c. 1870. One of a pair.
End-of-terrace four-bay three-storey house, c. 1830.
Detached three-bay three-storey over basement house, c. 1820, with stair return to rear. Now in part use as surgery.
End-of-terrace five-bay three-storey Georgian house, c. 1800, with stair return and two-storey return to rear.

NAME: Irish Permanent Building Society
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace three-bay two-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1825. Renovated, c. 1990, with pair of shopfronts inserted to ground floor.

NAME: Kilnacourt House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey over basement Georgian house, c. 1790. Renovated, c. 1875, with granite projecting porch added. In part use as offices from 1997 - 1999. Now disused and partly derelict following series of small fires. Group of detached outbuildings to side. Renovated, c. 1980, to accommodate commercial use. Ornamental gardens to site. Removed, c. 2000. Freestanding medieval stone statue to site. Now removed and relocated. Gateway to site, dismantled c. 2000.
Pair of freestanding carved limestone milestones, c. 1800, on triangular plans.

Semi-detached two-bay three-storey house, c. 1730, originally detached. Extended to rear comprising pair of two-storey returns. Now amalgamated with building to left. Group of detached outbuildings to rear.
Stable complex, c. 1870, comprising group of detached two-storey buildings with arcade, integral carriageways and bull's-eye window openings.

NAME: John Maher Veterinary Surgeon
COMPOSITION: Terraced five-bay two-storey house, c. 1840, with integral carriageway. Renovated, c. 1880, with façade enrichments added.
Terraced three-bay two-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1815. Renovated, c. 1990, with render removed.

NAME: Grange Lodge
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey over basement late-Georgian house, c. 1835. Group of detached outbuildings to site.
Pair of semi-detached three-bay two-storey houses, c. 1840. Detached coach house to rear.
Detached three-bay two-storey house, c. 1850. Extended to rear comprising two-storey return.

NAME: Presentation Convent
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey convent, c. 1880, on an L-shaped plan with central breakfront having statue over. Extended, c. 1975, with projecting porch and end bays added. Extended, c. 1980, with single-storey garage added to right and conservatory added to rear.

NAME: Saint Joseph's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached Gothic Revival Catholic church, built 1878, with bell tower. Renovated, c. 1985, with confessionals, transepts, chancel and sacristy projection added.

NAME: Bank of Ireland
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey Victorian bank, c. 1862, with advanced end bays and wing to rear. Architect was William Caldbeck and James Scanlan of Listowel the builder.

NAME: Mountmellick Town Hall
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey gable-fronted former town hall, c. 1863. Now in use as parish hall. Architect was William Caldbeck.

NAME: Mountmellick Methodist Church
COMPOSITION: Detached gable-fronted Methodist church, c. 1880, with gabled projecting porch.

NAME: Avonmore Home and Farm Supplies
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace six-bay three-storey house, c. 1885. Renovated and extended to rear, c. 1980, comprising two-storey split-level return with ground floor remodelled to accommodate commercial use.

End-of-terrace five-bay three-storey Georgian house, c. 1790, with single-bay single-storey bay to left, three-storey split-level return and stair return to rear.

NAME: Durrow Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, c. 1795, with tower, transept, curved chancel and vestry projection.

NAME: Castle Durrow
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay Tudor Revival gate lodge, c. 1835, with four-storey tower to side on a circular plan. Extended comprising single-storey range. Gateway to site comprising screen wall with castellations.

NAME: Durrow I.C.A. Hall
COMPOSITION: Detached single-storey gable-fronted former Methodist chapel, c. 1822, with gabled projecting porch. Extended to right. Now in use as library and hall.
Detached three-bay two-storey house, c. 1880, originally terraced.
End-of-terrace five-bay two-storey house, c. 1875, with integral carriageway.

NAME: Durrow F.C.A. Hall
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey former courthouse, c. 1820, with projecting porches. Now in use as F.C.A. hall.

NAME: Old Chapel Medical Centre
COMPOSITION: Detached single-storey house, c. 1885. Renovated, c. 1900, with timber shopfront inserted to ground floor. Now in use as surgery.

NAME: Mahony's
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay two-storey house, c. 1890. Renovated, c. 1890, with shopfront inserted to ground floor.

NAME: Tom Woods
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay two-storey house, c. 1840, with integral carriageway. Renovated, c. 1900, with timber shopfront inserted to ground floor.
Group of five terraced three-bay two-storey houses, c. 1880, on a stepped plan.

NAME: Church of the Holy Trinity
COMPOSITION: Detached early Gothic Revival Catholic church, dated 1839, on a cruciform plan with tower. Extended comprising single-storey range. Interior retains gallery.

NAME: Durrow Infant School
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay single-storey infant school, dated 1880. Three-bay two-storey house attached to side. Now vacant.

NAME: Durrow Pharmacy
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey house, c. 1830, with shopfront to ground floor. Renovated, c. 1980, with full-height projecting bay added to rear.

NAME: C. Shepard
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay two-storey house, c. 1850, with shopfront to part ground floor.

NAME: Durrow Inn
COMPOSITION: Terraced six-bay three-storey house, c. 1880, with integral carriageway. Renovated, c. 1985, with ground floor remodelled to accommodate commercial use.

NAME: The Copper Kettle
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, c. 1880. Renovated and amalgamated with building to right, c. 1985, with ground floor remodelled to accommodate use as restaurant.

NAME: Castle Durrow
COMPOSITION: Detached nine-bay two-storey over basement Queen Anne style house with dormer attic, c. 1716. Renovated and extended, c. 1875, with projecting porch added to front on a polygonal plan and lateral wings added. Converted to use as convent, c. 1925 - c. 1995. Now in private residential use.

NAME: Castle Durrow
COMPOSITION: Freestanding obelisk, c. 1810.

NAME: Claude's Seat
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Classical style gazebo, c. 1810, with round-headed arches to sides. Now in ruins.

NAME: All Saints Church of Ireland Church
COMPOSITION: Detached Georgian Gothic Church of Ireland church, dated 1821, with tower. Renovated, c. 1865, with chancel added.

NAME: Saint Brigid's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Detached Gothic Revival Catholic church, c. 1835, on a cruciform plan with steeple and sacristy projection over basement. Roof structure unusual and irregular, stained glass windows probably all by Mayer & Co Ltd. Munich.

NAME: Ballinakill School
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay single-storey Victorian former school, c. 1890, with two-bay gabled projecting porch to front and return to rear. Now in use as hall.

NAME: Ballinakill School
COMPOSITION: Detached single-storey gable-fronted school, dated 1889, with gabled projecting porch.
Terraced three-bay two-storey house, c. 1875, with full-height return to rear. Group of detached outbuildings to rear.
End-of-terrace five-bay two-storey house, c. 1820. Extensively renovated, c. 1985.
End-of-terrace four-bay three-storey late-Georgian house, c. 1800.

NAME: Stanhope Bridge
COMPOSITION: Single-arch road bridge over river, dated 1784, with lintel.

NAME: Stanhope Arch
COMPOSITION: Single-arch bridge over stream, c. 1815, with castellations and diamond-shaped panel.

NAME: Ballinakill Castle
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached medieval tower house, c. 1680. Now in ruins. Originally five stories high, constructed of roughly coursed stone with dressed limestone quoins. Two gun loops visible on ground and first floor; large window to second floor.

NAME: Moneycleare House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey over basement late-Georgian house, c. 1820. Extended to right comprising single-bay two-storey range.
